function mostVisitedRoom(n, meetings) {
    meetings.sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0]);
    const pq = [];
    const rooms = Array(n).fill(0);

    for (const [start, end] of meetings) {
        while (pq.length && pq[0][0] <= start) {
            const [_, room] = pq.shift();
            rooms[room]++;
        }
        pq.push([end, pq.length % n]);
        pq.sort((a, b) => a[0] - b[0]);
    }

    return rooms.indexOf(Math.max(...rooms));
}
```

    The solution uses a priority queue to manage the state of the rooms. First, we sort the meetings by the start time. For each meeting, we check if there are any rooms that will be available by the meeting's start time. If so, we increment the counter for that room in the `rooms` array, which tracks the number of meetings held in each room.

After looping through all the rooms, we check the `rooms` array to find the room with the highest count of meetings. If there are multiple rooms with the same maximum count, we return the room with the lowest index (room number).

The time complexity of this solution is O(M * log(M)), where M is the number of meetings, mainly due to sorting the meetings and managing the priority queue. The space complexity is O(N+M), where N is the number of rooms, and M is the number of meetings.

